            "heading": "FAQ",
            "icon": "question_mark",
            "content": "<p><strong>Q: What is Different About Catfishing?<br/>A: </strong>Catfishing is a bottom-oriented style of fishing that relies heavily on scent and taste rather than sight, since catfish are equipped with thousands of taste buds and sensitive whisker-like barbels to locate food. This makes it unique from other fishing styles that often depend on lures mimicking visual movement or flash. Catfishing also tends to involve heavier gear, stout rods, and weighted rigs designed to keep bait anchored on or near the bottom where catfish patrol and feed.<br/></p><p><strong>Q:</strong> <strong>What types of baits are used for Catfish?<br/>A: </strong>Catfish are notorious for being attracted to strong-smelling baits, making stink baits, dip baits, and punch baits some of the most popular choices among catfish anglers. Cut bait — chunks of shad, bluegill, or other baitfish — is also widely used and highly effective, especially for larger channel and blue catfish. Live bait like nightcrawlers, crawfish, and frogs round out the options, while prepared dough baits and chicken liver are classic go-to choices for anglers of all experience levels.<br/></p>",
